Big-O :   This is what most people know.

                                    But Google interviewers sometimes go further.
            
             Big-O represents   :       The upper bound on growth.
            
            It tells us         :       The algorithm will not grow faster than this asymptotically.


Big-Theta (Θ)   : Big-Theta is a tight bound.

                      It means  : Upper Bound                        
                                    AND                        
                                    Lower Bound
                                    
                    Example: for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
                        
                     Always executes : n
                                       Not more.                        
                                       Not less.

                        Therefore : Θ(n)

Big-Omega (Ω)   : Big-Omega represents the lower bound.

                        Meaning: The algorithm will take at least this much work.
                        
                        Example: Searching in an unsorted array.
                        
                        Best case: Target is first element :     Ω(1)
                        Worst case:   Last element.        :   O(n)                        
                        Average : Θ(n)

This distinction becomes useful when discussing best, average, and worst-case behavior.
