Amortized Analysis

            This is one of the favorite follow-up topics for experienced Java engineers.

            Question:      Why is            
                                    ArrayList.add()
            
                        considered : O(1)            
                        when resizing copies the entire array?
            
            Good observation!
                       
            Imagine
                        Capacity
                        
                        4
                        1
                        2
                        3
                        4
                        
            Now insert
                        
                        5
                        
            Java allocates a larger array (typically ~1.5× bigger in modern JDKs) and copies the existing elements before adding the new one.
                        
            That single insertion is O(n) because of the copy.
                        
            But it doesn't happen on every insertion.
                        
            Most calls simply place the new element in the next available slot:
                        
                        O(1)
                        
                        O(1)
                        
                        O(1)
                        
                        O(n)
                        
                        O(1)
                        
                        O(1)
                        
                        ...
                        
            If you spread the occasional expensive resize across many cheap insertions, the average cost per insertion remains O(1). 
            That's what amortized O(1) means.

Interview Question

                        Why isn't
                        
                                    ArrayList.add()                        
                                    always                        
                                    O(n)
                        
                        Because resizing is infrequent.                        
                                    Most insertions don't require copying.                        
                                    The occasional expensive operation is distributed over many inexpensive operations.
                        
                        Hence:                        
                                    Amortized O(1)



