Complexity Cheat Sheet

                        | Operation                     | Time     | Space |
                        | ----------------------------- | -------- | ----- |
                        | Array Access                  | O(1)     | O(1)  |
                        | Array Traversal               | O(n)     | O(1)  |
                        | Binary Search (sorted array)  | O(log n) | O(1)  |
                        | HashMap Lookup (average)      | O(1)     | O(n)  |
                        | HashMap Lookup (worst case)   | O(n)     | O(n)  |
                        | ArrayList `add()` (amortized) | O(1)     | O(1)  |
                        | ArrayList Insert at Beginning | O(n)     | O(1)  |



Google Interview Tip of the Day

            When asked for the complexity of a solution, don't stop at "O(n)".

            A strong L5 answer sounds like this:

                             "The algorithm performs a single pass over the input, 
                                    so the time complexity is O(n). It stores each element in a HashSet, 
                                    causing the additional memory usage to grow linearly with the input size, 
                                    so the space complexity is O(n). T
                                    he lookup and insertion operations are O(1) 
                                    on average because HashSet is backed by a hash table."

                        Notice how that answer includes reasoning, not just the final result.

